nguage history and variation linguistics. In addition, it offers an analysis of the processes underlying the public debate from the perspectives of language sociology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a FA license: uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/free-access-policy uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGerman languagexDiscourse analysisvCongresses. 0aGerman languagexUsagevCongresses. 0aGerman languagexVariationvCongresses. 0aGerman languagey21st centuryvCongresses. 0aLinguistic changezGermanyvCongresses. 4aSprachverfall. 4aSprachwandel. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aLanguage decline.  alanguage change.1 aBelica, Cyril, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetzel, Dirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDammel, Antje, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Winifred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurrell, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichinger, Ludwig M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJäger, Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Wolf Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKleiner, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKupietz, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanger, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLenz, Alexandra N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLüngen, Harald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aN